['Geotem Anomaly ', 'LOCATION ', 'GEOLOGICAL FINDINGS ', 'This linear EM feature lies just off the eastern edge of a magnetic bearing serpentinite (formerly a body of ultramafic) Biotite gneisses and calc-silicates, interbedded lie to the eastern side of the conductor while a wedge of Cambro-Ordovician metasediments/meta- volcanoclastics lie to the west, overlain by Devonian grits. ', 'Small quantities of biotite gneiss and amphibolite in small erosion gulleys -100m to the east. ', 'Biotite gneiss in creeks nearby. ', 'Biotite gneiss, calc-silicate gneiss and pegmatites, along with small amounts of sheared granite. ', 'No outcrop. ', 'No outcrop. ', 'Interlayered amphibolite and biotite schist with some probable marble. Small amounts of sheared granite. ', 'Interlayered sheared granite with thin bands of pelitic and psammitic schists and banded porphyroblastic amphibolite, could be in the Balcooma metavolcanics. ', 'To the east of the conductors lies a sequence of sheared amphibolite and granite along with biotite schists and quartzo-feldspathic granofels. Calc-silicates and sheared granite lie to the west. ', 'Linear marble units lie to each side of the conductor. In between there are small amounts of biotite schist/pegmatites and well foliated amphibolites. ', 'As above. ', 'Biotite schists, garnet-muscovite schists and pegmatite surround this particular GEOTEM anomaly. Soil sampling returned 200m at 290ppm Zn, with up to 371ppm Zn. ', 'No outcrop. ', 'Small amounts of granite and calc-silicates. ', 'Biotite gneisses and amphibolite ', 'No outcrop. ']

A 2 m wide magnetite-garnet BIF unit is present at 166-168 m depth with sphalerite mineralisation. (6 m @ 3.93% Zn from 162 - 168 m). No other mineralised intersections of BIF units are present in the hole. The BIF was intersected early than expected from the magnetic data but it is still the only spike in the magnetic susceptbility readings and explains adequately the model. Mg and Ni rich zones are found towards the EOH associated with spinafix texture ultramafic bodies. ', 'ANP 465 has intersected a very similar Zn rich BIF from ANP 435 in the original Spell paddock drill hole. This drillhole does not upgrade the potential of a mineralised package in the prospect. ', 'SPELL PADDOCK ', 'Best surface geochem in magnetic quiet area ', 'ANP 466 intersected a sequence of garnet bearing psammites and psammitic schists with thin amphibolite and quartz-feldspar pegmatite bodies throughout the hole. No apparent mineralisation, other than minor pyrite associated with the amphibolites. ', 'ANP 466 has tested the same stratigraphy present the spell paddock area without any significant geochemistry. The nature of the geochem anomaly still unclear. ', 'SPELL PADDOCK ', 'western magnetic limb ', 'ANP435, PECU06, ANP461, ANP461 ', 'ANP 469 intersected a sequence of variably magnetic amphibolites and psammites/quartzites with minor pegmatite veining zones. Variable foliation and shearing is present at the amphibolites. Towards the end of the hole, a wide amphibolite interval with spinafix textures and anomalous Ni and Mg would corroborate ultramafic intrusives. ', 'Only minor anomalous Zn (maximum up to 417 ppm) and spotty Pb is present at a garnet bearing biotite schist and biotite psammite with pyrite from 144 to m. Due to the lack of any other significant mineralised intervals. No further work is planned. ']

['Completed test on under reamer before putting in hole. Arms opened up perfectly. Under reamer working normally. ', 'RIH with under reamer to production interval depth of 160m ', 'Setup mud gas detection system. ', "Replaced female fitting from air hose, which connects onto male part on agitator. had a suspicion that the old fitting wasn't locking onto the male part properly and not letting all the air through to turn the spindle. Agitator appears to be working fine now. ", 'Started under reaming at 160m. ', 'Gas readings up to 25 gas units (10 LEL) ', 'Reaming appears to be going slower than anticipated. ', 'Stopped under reaming. Something happened down the hole and arms are not engaging anymore. Driller believes that arms may have snapped off. ', 'POOH to check under reamer. ', "Rang Kent Anson. He is going into the office to check if DTH has another set as doesn't have an after hours number for them. ", 'OOH. All three arms have snapped off at the base. The pins are still there. The driller had no pull down on the under reamer at all while he was under reaming. ', 'Called John Dingley. The arms that were on the under reamer were brand-new and he got the last set from DTH. He also sent the old set back to Brisbane on Friday be repaired. ', 'Driller and offsiders left site. They are going to wait and find out what we want to do with hole. ', 'It is possible that flexure in the arms from reaming on edge of the arms in the larger hole may have been the cause. We are unsure at the moment what the cause of breakage until we inspect the arms. Russell also noted that the arms appeared to have been welded together which would of caused a weakness in them. Kent will inspect them as soon as he can to see if this was the case. ']

', 'Spoke to driller about the slow drilling and concerns about breaking the under- reaming arms. ', 'Stopped under-reaming. In 2hrs and 40min only 4 meters was gained. At the rate it is unfeasible to complete the well using the current drilling program. ', 'Contacted Ron Prefontaine and discussed completion options for the well. It decided to ream the production section from 6" to 1/2" with the 9 1/2" bit then ream the upper section of the well where the swelling clays are present It will attempted to control and stabilize these clays with mud before running casing. ', 'To check to whether or not the clays have been stabilized a caliper log may be into the well before the screens and casing. Tripped out of hole. ', 'Nipple down BOP ']

Although the rank and quality of Group IV coals vary greatly, they are characterised by their lower vitrinite content in the raw coal and generally low levels of sulphur.
